Design Limitations – Agentic AI Browser Extension Platform
1. Browser Extension Environment Limitations

Browser extensions operate within sandboxed browser environments, restricting direct access to system resources and enterprise applications.

Extensions rely on DOM access and browser APIs, which may change depending on browser updates or application UI changes.

Enterprise browser policies may restrict extension capabilities such as script injection, cross-origin requests, or external API calls.

Extension execution is limited to user browser sessions, meaning agents cannot operate when the browser is closed or inactive.

2. Data Security and Privacy Limitations

Sensitive business data processed within the browser must comply with data masking and redaction policies before being used by AI agents.

Raw enterprise data cannot be transmitted to external LLM providers unless explicitly approved.

Browser storage mechanisms (localStorage, sessionStorage, IndexedDB) are not suitable for storing sensitive business data.

Client-side masking may not guarantee 100% coverage of sensitive information due to DOM variability or application design.

3. AI Model Limitations

Large Language Models may produce non-deterministic responses and occasional hallucinations.

Model reasoning is dependent on quality and completeness of provided context.

LLM outputs may require validation against enterprise systems before execution.

Model drift and updates from external providers may impact behavior over time.

4. Authentication and Session Constraints

Authentication must rely on enterprise SSO mechanisms such as SAML or OIDC.

Browser-based session management is limited by browser session lifetime and security policies.

Session tokens must follow strict timeout policies such as:

inactivity timeout

absolute session expiration

token refresh cycles

5. Agent Execution Limitations

Agents operating in browser environments depend on UI structure and DOM consistency, making them sensitive to UI changes.

Autonomous execution capabilities must remain restricted by policy guardrails to prevent unauthorized actions.

Agents cannot bypass enterprise access controls or privileged authorization boundaries.

Some enterprise workflows may require server-side orchestration rather than client-only execution.

6. Compliance and Governance Constraints

All agent actions must be auditable and traceable through logging and monitoring systems.

The platform must comply with enterprise policies related to:

data protection

encryption

access control

audit requirements

Deployment must follow internal CI/CD and packaging approval processes for browser extensions.

7. Deployment and Packaging Limitations

Extensions must be distributed through approved internal enterprise channels.

Unpacked extensions or sideloaded builds are not allowed in production environments.

All builds must pass security scanning tools such as:

SAST

dependency scanning

vulnerability scanning

8. Integration Limitations

Direct integration with internal systems may require additional API gateways or service layers.

Some enterprise systems may restrict automation or programmatic access.

Network policies and firewall restrictions may limit external service connectivity.

9. Observability and Monitoring Constraints

Logging must exclude sensitive user or business data.

Monitoring systems must be integrated with enterprise observability platforms.

AI decision-making must support traceability and explainability for audit and compliance.

10. Fail-Safe and Operational Limitations

Agents must support safe fallback mechanisms if errors or unexpected conditions occur.

Emergency shutdown controls must exist to disable agents during incidents.

System must support rollback capabilities if automated actions cause unintended outcomes.

