Design Constraints & Limitations
1. Regulatory and CTC Approvals

Deployment of browser extensions in enterprise VDI environments requires additional firm-wide regulatory approvals and CTC (Cyber Technology Controls) reviews. Unlike standard applications, browser extensions must pass enhanced security and governance checks before production deployment.

2. Data Minimization and DOM Scope

The extension must strictly follow a data minimization principle:

Only parse and process the minimum required DOM elements.

Sensitive or confidential fields must never be extracted or transmitted.

DOM scraping should be restricted to approved elements and attributes.

3. Compliance for Model Integrations

Integration with AI models must follow strict compliance rules:

Highly confidential or restricted enterprise data must never be transmitted to external AI services without explicit approval.

All sensitive attributes must be redacted or anonymized before AI processing.

AI integrations must comply with internal data governance and AI usage policies.

4. Handling Highly Confidential Attributes

Sensitive enterprise data requires additional safeguards:

Access must be protected using Role-Based Access Control (RBAC).

Data must be encrypted during storage and transmission.

DLP (Data Loss Prevention) checks and redaction mechanisms must be applied before any outbound communication.

5. Prompt Confirmation and User Action Workflow

Any operation involving external data transmission or irreversible automation must require:

Explicit user confirmation

Clear visibility of what data will be transmitted

Approval before executing sensitive agent actions

6. Multi-Tab, Concurrency, and Context Management

Browser extensions operate in multi-tab environments, introducing concurrency challenges:

Session context must be isolated per browser tab.

Agent state must be synchronized to prevent race conditions or data leaks.

Workflow state must be carefully coordinated across tabs.

7. Agent Memory Management

Agent memory must follow strict boundaries:

Memory should be limited to user session and task scope.

Long-term storage must use encrypted, enterprise-approved storage services.

Access controls must prevent unauthorized cross-agent data sharing.

8. Observability, Auditing, and Fail-Safe Controls

The platform must support strong operational governance:

Centralized telemetry and logging for agent activity.

Audit trails for agent decisions and actions.

Fail-safe mechanisms and circuit breakers to stop agents if policy violations or system errors occur.

9. Testing and Performance Constraints

The platform must undergo comprehensive validation:

Cross-browser compatibility testing.

Validation of asynchronous UI behavior.

Security testing for browser APIs and extension permissions.

Performance testing to ensure agents remain responsive under concurrent usage.

10. Browser Compatibility and Deployment Controls

The solution must maintain compatibility across enterprise-approved browsers:

Chrome

Edge

Firefox (where required)

Deployment must support:

Extension packaging and signing

Policy-based updates

Controlled rollbacks

Compatibility with enterprise VDI environments

